"Abstract Contractors, be they individuals or large IT consultancies, are frequently used to help organizations develop bespoke software solutions to meet their requirements. Unfortunately, despite the best efforts of the legal and risk management professions, such services are often provided without the benefit of a property drawn-up contract. One of the most important aspects of such engagements, namely ownership of the copyright in the deliverables produced as a result of the services provided, can thus be left uncertain, but with the assumption that, as the contractor will have been the ‘author’ of the deliverables in question for the purposes of the Copyright Designs and Patents Act 1988, it will acquire copyright in them, and the Client will simply acquire a licence to use them of indeterminate scope, despite having funded their production. However, an unreported case from the Court of Appeal at the end of 1999 has opened up new possibilities for clients who find themselves in this position, and in particular raises the prospect of arguing that there has been an equitable assignment of copyright."
